# Select the food groups which we want to explore and the variables for those which we want to compare. Make a subset for these variables filtered by the focus food groups.

usda_nutr_sub <- usda_nutrients %>%
  filter(food_group == c("Vegetables and Vegetable Products",
                         "Baked Products")) %>% 
  select(food_group, energy_kcal: sugar_g, calcium_mg, magnesium_mg, phosphorus_mg)
usda_nutr_pca <- prcomp(usda_nutr_sub[,-1], scale = TRUE)

usda_nutr_pca

fviz_eig(usda_nutr_pca) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "PCA Varience of Food Group Nutrients", 
       subtitle = "Percentage of Varience Explained by Each Principal Component", 
       x = "Dimensions", y = "Percentage of Explained Variences") +
  
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"),
    plot.title = element_text(size=14, face="bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold.italic"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = -1),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = 2),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"),
    legend.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"))

# Use 'cbind' to combine the original subset dataframe with the PCA scores from PC1 and PC2:

usda_nutr_bind <- cbind(usda_nutr_sub, usda_nutr_pca$x[,1:2])
ggplot(data = usda_nutr_bind,
       aes(x = PC1, y = PC2,
           color = food_group,
           fill = food_group)) +
  stat_ellipse(geom = "polygon",
               color = "black",
               alpha = 0.5) +
  geom_point(shape = 21,
             color = "black",
             alpha = 0.6) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Probability of Nutrients by Food Groups", 
       subtitle = "PCA of Grouped Variables", 
       x = "PC1 (42.12%)", y = "PC2 (23.44%)") +
  
  scale_color_manual(name = "Food Group",
                       labels = c("Baked Products", "Vegetables and Vegetable Products"),
                       values = c("lightcoral", "turquoise3")) +
  
  scale_fill_manual(name = "Food Group",
                       labels = c("Baked Products", "Vegetables and Vegetable Products"),
                       values = c("lightcoral", "turquoise3")) +
  
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"),
    plot.title = element_text(size=14, face="bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold.italic"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = -1),
    axis.title.y = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = 2),
    strip.text.x = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold.italic"),

fviz_pca_var(usda_nutr_pca,
             col.var = "contrib", # Color by contributions to the PC
             gradient.cols = c("#00AFBB", "#E7B800", "#FC4E07"),
             repel = TRUE) +    # Avoid text overlapping
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Contributions to PCA", 
       subtitle = "Variable Contribution Principal Components Analysis", 
       x = "PC1 (42.12%)", y = "PC2 (23.44%)") +
  
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"),
    plot.title = element_text(size=14, face="bold"),

# Hmmm let's try something else (this requires ggfortify): 

usda_nutr_biplot <- autoplot(usda_nutr_pca,
                             data = usda_nutr_sub,
                             size = 0.5,
                             alpha = 0.5,
                             colour = "food_group",
                             label = FALSE,
                             loadings.label = TRUE,
                             loadings.colour = "red",
                             loadings.label.size = 3,
                             loadings.label.colour = "black",
                             loadings.label.repel = TRUE) +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(-0.05, 0.05)) +
  scale_x_continuous(limits = c(-0.05, 0.075)) +
  theme_bw() +
  labs(title = "Biplot: Nutrient Value of Food Groups", 
       subtitle = "PCA Analysis of Nutrient Variables", 
       x = "PC1 (42.12%)", y = "PC2 (23.44%)") +
  
  scale_color_manual(name = "Food Group",
                       labels = c("Baked Products", "Vegetables and Vegetable Products"),
                       values = c("lightcoral", "turquoise3")) +
  
  theme(text = element_text(family = "serif"),
    plot.title = element_text(size=14, face="bold"),
    plot.subtitle = element_text(size = 9, face = "bold.italic"),
    axis.title.x = element_text(size=10, face="bold", vjust = -1),
